SIMPLE: refine
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Refine
<hw>Re*fine"</hw> <pr>(r?*f?n")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Refined</conjf>
<pr>(-find")</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Refining</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Pref. <ets>re-</ets> +
<ets>fine</ets> to make fine: cf. F. <ets>raffiner</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To reduce to a fine, unmixed, or pure state; to free
from impurities; to free from dross or alloy; to separate from
extraneous matter; to purify; to defecate; <as>as, to <ex>refine</ex>
gold or silver; to <ex>refine</ex> iron; to <ex>refine</ex> wine or
sugar.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will bring the third part through the fire, and will
<qex>refine</qex> them as silver is <qex>refined</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Zech. xiii. 9.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To purify from what is gross, coarse, vulgar,
inelegant, low, and the like; to make elegant or exellent; to polish;
<as>as, to <ex>refine</ex> the manners, the language, the style, the
taste, the intellect, or the moral feelings</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Love <qex>refines</qex>⟦br⟧
The thoughts, and heart enlarges.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To purify; clarify; polish; ennoble.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Refine</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Refine
<hw>Re*fine"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To become pure; to
be cleared of feculent matter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So the pure, limpid stream, when foul with stains,⟦br⟧
Works itself clear, and, as it runs, <qex>refines</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To improve in accuracy, delicacy, or
excellence.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Chaucer <qex>refined</qex> on Boccace, and mended his stories.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But let a lord once own the happy lines,⟦br⟧
How the wit brightens! How the style <qex>refines</qex>!</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To affect nicety or subtilty in thought or
language.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧He makes another paragraph about our
<xex>refining</xex> in controversy.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Atterbury.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Refined</ent>⟦br⟧
